text: Omg, this looks like sooooo good and I'm not even black!!! Like, I know it's a black person movie like Straight Outta Compton but funnier, but even tho Straight Outta Compton was a black person movie, I still thought it was good... Like, I didn't get all of the slang and stuff, but it was still pretty badass and so was the soundtrack for it. I feel like if someone like me, who is as white as the light is bright (lol, like my fave film is Napoleon Dynamite, which is totally a white kid film - even tho i'm sure some black ppl liked it too) just goes to show that maybe we as a society are moving towards more "cultural appropriation" in films (i hope I used that term correctly, without offence). Like, even the fact that I think that this is a brilliant spin on the film. The white version of Fifty Shades wasn't even that good honestly.... I think this black version will be much better. So I'm gonna see it. What do you guys think about the white vs. black versions, which are you more excited to see and what do you think about us, as white folks, moving towards cultural acceptance and embracing the "other" and going out to see things like this or Straight Outta Compton and enjoying other cultures and their work, rather than just sticking to the norm for us? I don't mean for this to be offensive, I just wanna write my next essay for school on this idea of embracing and finding the "other" as we progress in society even tho there is still so much racism in this sinister world? Discuss! Go! lol. - Candis XO
